            <fr:title text="Finitary Algebraic Theory">Finitary Algebraic Theory</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>A finitary signature is a collection <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ]]></fr:tex> of operation symbols with assigned <html:em>arities</html:em> which are natural numbers</html:p>
            <html:p>Given a signature, we can form the type of trees <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^*X]]></fr:tex>. A finitary algebraic theory is a signature with a collection of axioms, which are pairs of trees <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^*X]]></fr:tex> for finite <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
            <html:p>An <html:em>algebra</html:em> of a theory <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {A} = (\Sigma , E)]]></fr:tex> consists of a carrier <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, for each operation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma (n)]]></fr:tex> an operation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma  : A^n \to  A]]></fr:tex> such that the induced equations from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E]]></fr:tex> are all satisfied. A homomorphism of algebras is a function that commutes with all of the operations. These form into a category <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\mathcal {A}-)\textrm {Alg}]]></fr:tex> with a forgetful functor <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U : \textrm {Alg} \to  \textrm {Set}]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p>A <html:em>free algebra</html:em> for a set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a left adjoint to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> at <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Free algebras always exist: they can be constructed as a quotient of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Sigma ^*X]]></fr:tex>, but it is useful when possible to come up with an equivalent description of free algebras as "normal forms" of these quotiented trees.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
